#1 Resected rectal adenocarcinoma (T3, N1(1 of 38), M0)
I have reviewed all of the above in-depth with Mr. Tracy Burnett through an interpreter as well as Dr. Morales.  At this point Mr. Tracy Burnett's scan does not show any evidence of recurrent metastatic disease, but there does appear to be some air in the bladder which is indeterminate.
From our perspective, we would like to start adjuvant chemotherapy in the form of FOLFOX for four to six-months.  Mr. Tracy Burnett does plan on staying in Albany for this treatment.  He notes at this point he does not feel that he is physically ready for chemotherapy, and he would like to delay this for an additional two-weeks.  I think this is overall acceptable, particularly in light of his other issues, mostly pain and depression that need to be better controlled, but I did indicate to Mr. Tracy Burnett that we would not want to wait more than six-weeks before initiating adjuvant treatment.  He understands this and would be agreeable to starting treatment if he has an additional couple of weeks to recover.  I also think this is a reasonable request considering his protracted hospital course and only recent hospital dismissal.  I will see him back later this afternoon with Dr. Sinclair.  We will discuss the overall plan and decide on an appropriate appointment for return for chemotherapy and Port-A-Cath placement.
#2 Pain
Mr. Tracy Burnett has chronic pain which does not seem to be well-controlled with his current pain regimen.  He has been taking narcotics preoperatively and had struggled with pain while hospitalized.  Currently his regimen of 20-mg of OxyContin twice-a-day is insufficiently controlling his pain.  I think that he would be best served by a referral back to our colleagues in the Pain Clinic for management.  In the interim I have refilled his OxyContin 20-mg tablet prescription, and he asked whether or not he could take this three times a day as he has been doing.  I thought this would be an acceptable plan until he sees our colleagues in Pain Clinic who will probably readjust his regimen.  He is comfortable with this at this point.
I have cautioned Mr. Tracy Burnett that all of the care providers are concerned about the potential for long-term narcotic addiction, particularly given his young age.  I do think at this point he still has residual pain-related to his surgery, but ultimately the goal would be to remove him from all narcotics.  He overall is agreeable to this plan, but at this point feels that his pain is suboptimally controlled and significantly negatively impacting his overall quality of life contributing to his sense of fatigue and overall depression.  Hopefully our colleagues in the Greenville Confederate Hospital can help us manage this pain situation.
#3 Depression
Mr. Tracy Burnett is symptomatic with depression.  I think it is related to his situation as well as inadequately controlled pain.  I have decided to start him on Celexa 20-mg daily.  I have cautioned him about the side-effects and also that it will take four to six-weeks before we note a significant improvement.  He is agreeable to this and actually also endorses the need for antidepressants.  He notes that he has no inclination for suicidal ideation and is overall feels well-supported by his family.
#4 Nutrition
Mr. Tracy Burnett is significantly malnourished.  Preoperatively he struggled with this and had subsequent significant weight-loss.  I have encouraged him to eat more and encouraged him to use supplemental Carnation Instant Breakfast or Boost or Ensure in addition to his food intake to help him continue to gain weight.  He is agreeable to this.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: No, not interested in additional information.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

