[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Burnett Burnett is a very pleasant 38-year-old male from New Smyrna Beach.  He has no prior medical history.
1.  February 2010, presented locally in New Smyrna Beach with a one-year history of change in bowel habits with increasing constipation and bloody stools.  Colonoscopy performed identified a 5-cm rectal mass.  Biopsies confirmed adenocarcinoma.  A CT-scan of chest, abdomen, and pelvis; MRI/PET scan negative for distant metastasis.  EUS performed identifying a T4 (with questionable prostate involvement), N1 rectal cancer by EUS criteria, CEA 18.4.
2.  April 2010, E-consult to Dr. Sinclair of Colorectal Surgery recommended neoadjuvant chemotherapy and radiation and surgery.  The patient did not pursue any treatment locally, nor did he come to the HC.
3.  June 9, 2010, presented to the HC with increasing abdominal pain, perineal pain, back and left leg pain, and increasing problems with constipation and blood as well as difficulty urinating.  He had a 50-pound progressive weight-loss over the last three-months.
4.  June 9, 2010, CT of the chest, abdomen, and pelvis identifying closer involvement of the known rectal cancer with seminal vesicles but no evidence of distant metastasis.
5.  June 10, 2010, colonoscopy performed showing a large rectal cancer 5-cm from the anal verge occupying 50% of the circumference.  Biopsy again performed confirmed adenocarcinoma.  Multiple other polyps seen but no carpet of polyps.  CEA 48.
6.  June 11, 2010, seen by Dr. Reynolds of Colorectal Surgery, who recommended neoadjuvant chemotherapy, radiation, and surgery.
7.  June 11, 2010, MRI performed showing a mass 1.5-cm from the anal verge, extending over 5.5 cm in length with invasion into the mesorectal fat with extension to involve the right seminal vesicles and enlarged perirectal lymph nodes.  No evidence of distant metastasis.  Immunohistochemical staining for DNA mismatch appears negative.  Lynch syndrome deemed unlikely.
8.  June 15, 2010, evaluated by Dr. Markham of Radiation Oncology.  Recommended neoadjuvant chemotherapy and radiation with possible IORT; scheduled to start radiation on June 21, 2010.
9.  June 16, 2010, evaluated by Medical Genetics.  Lynch syndrome ruled out.  Current testing for FAP and MYH undergoing.
10.  June 16, 2010, evaluation by Dr. Mccubbin of Medical Oncology, who concurred with overall plan and recommended infusional 5-FU as a radiosensitizer, surgery, and adjuvant chemotherapy in the form of FOLFOX.
11.  June 21, 2010, initiated external-beam radiation and concurrent infusional 5-FU through July 29, 2010.  Overall tolerated well.
12.  September 1, 2010, taken by Dr. Gerber and Dr. Markham for a complex APR with en bloc resection of the seminal vesicles on the right and left and end colostomy with IORT along the seminal prostate margin.  Seminal vesicles ultimately not involved.  Surgical pathology noting grade 3 of 4 adenocarcinoma forming a 5.3- x 3.2- x 1.4-cm mass in the rectum with treatment effect involving one of 38 regional lymph nodes invading through the muscular propria with no lymphovascular invasion evident.  Negative surgical margins, although 0.4 radial margin subsequently boosted with IORT.  Had protracted recovery and hospital course due to persistent pain and ileus.
Mr. Tracy Burnett returns in the outpatient setting for further evaluation and management.  He notes he was dismissed in the hospital approximately two-weeks ago, and he has not noticed a significant improvement.  His biggest complaint is excessive pain which is both constant in his abdominal area and pelvic area, both legs, and his anus.  He characterizes this as a 5 out of 10 constantly.  He also has intermittent sharp sudden quite severe pain which he characterizes as a 5 out of 10 which comes and goes.  He was given 30-mg twice-a-day of OxyContin when dismissed from the hospital but ran out of this prescription and has been taking 20-mg of OxyContin twice-a-day. This is inadequately controlling his pain.  He has not used supplemental oxycodone as he notes this gave him palpitations in the past.  He was managed by our colleagues in the Greenville Confederate Hospital while hospitalized, and he felt that they were very beneficial with their recommendations and would like to see them again for ongoing management.
He has a functioning colostomy in place and using MiraLAX daily and will have liquid bowel movements.  This is problematic for him and requires him to change his colostomy bag frequently.  He is somewhat disturbed by the fact that he was only given enough supplies for a month, and he feels as though he is going through these supplies quickly.  He does not wish to see the stoma therapy nurses again.  He notes overall his appetite is low but improving.  He has been able to maintain his weight.  He had one occasion of vomiting, but this was accompanied by severe pain.  Other than that he has had no nausea or vomiting.  He has had no fevers or night sweats.  He has no chest pain, shortness-of-breath, or peripheral edema.
His energy level is overall low.  He finds himself very depressed.  He notes he does not have much interest in any of the activities he previously found joy in and will cry often and often daily.  He notes he is having issues with urination, will have pain at the end of urination, and also notes air coming out at the end of urination.  He has not noticed any hematuria.

